# Why Should Abortions Be Legal? A Comprehensive Report

## Introduction

The legality of abortion remains one of the most contentious public policy issues worldwide, intersecting ethics, health, human rights, and socio-economic factors. This report presents a detailed, evidence-based analysis of why abortions should be legal, emphasizing public health, safety, human rights, and socio-economic benefits. Drawing on extensive scientific research, public health data, and policy analyses, this report aims to provide an objective and comprehensive understanding of the critical reasons supporting legal abortion access.

---

## 1. Public Health and Safety Benefits of Legal Abortion

### 1.1 Reduction in Maternal Mortality and Morbidity

Before abortion was legalized in the United States, an estimated 200,000 to 1,200,000 illegal abortions were performed annually, mostly in unsafe conditions by unskilled practitioners ([Tyrer, 1992](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/12340404/)). These illegal abortions were associated with high complication rates, including sepsis caused by *Clostridium perfringens*, which led to gas gangrene and significant mortality. Annually, over 100 women died from abortion complications prior to legalization, with actual numbers likely higher due to underreporting.

After the 1973 Roe v. Wade decision, legal abortion procedures increased dramatically, reaching over 1.3 million annually by 1983, with a marked decrease in abortion-related deaths from 90 in 1972 to 16 in 1980 ([Cates, Grimes, & Schulz, 2003](https://doi.org/10.1363/3502503)). Legal abortions carry an especially low risk of death, particularly when performed in the first trimester, with mortality rates approximately seven times lower than childbirth ([Tyrer, 1992](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/12340404/)).

| Indicator                      | Illegal Abortion (Pre-1970) | Legal Abortion (Post-1973) | Childbirth (1970s)       |
|-------------------------------|-----------------------------|----------------------------|-------------------------|
| Estimated Annual Procedures    | ~1,000,000+                 | ~1,300,000                 | N/A                     |
| Annual Deaths                  | >100                        | <20                        | Higher than abortion     |
| Mortality Rate (per 100,000)   | Up to 30 times higher risk  | 1.9                       | 7 times higher than abortion |

*Table 1: Comparison of mortality rates and safety between illegal abortion, legal abortion, and childbirth.*

### 1.2 Decline in Complications and Hospitalizations

Legal abortion has led to a significant reduction in septic abortion complications treated in emergency rooms and hospitals. The availability of safe, regulated procedures has virtually eliminated many of the severe infections and injuries previously common in illegal abortions ([Cates et al., 2003](https://doi.org/10.1363/3502503)).

